{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"47248127-b361-41c2-92b0-8fc5081f6f25","content":"Your project uses **MSTest 3.8 on Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP)**. MTP has a built-in hang detection option. Run:\n\n```\ndotnet test -- --hang-dump-timeout 5m\n```\n\nThis tells MTP to monitor test execution and produce a hang dump if no progress is made for 5 minutes, helping you identify which test is stuck. The `--` separates `dotnet test` args from MTP-specific args.\n\nYou can also add `--hang-dump-path ./dumps` to control where the dump file is saved.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"eafc63d7-89bb-431d-b80d-6302c84dc9e4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is using MSTest 3.8.0 with Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) runner. They want a hang timeout of 5 minutes.\n\nWith MTP, you can use `--hang-dump-timeout` CLI option to detect hanging tests. This will create a dump file when a test hangs beyond the specified timeout.\n\nThe command would be:\n\n```\ndotnet test --hang-dump-timeout 5m\n```\n\nOr they could also use `--timeout` to set a global test execution timeout.\n\nLet me think about this more carefully. The `--hang-dump-timeout` option is the right one for detecting hanging tests with MTP. \n\nSo `--hang-dump-timeout` monitors for inactivity and generates a dump file when tests appear to hang, giving you diagnostic information to investigate the issue.","outputTokens":317},"id":"482ea17a-b3fe-482d-84a1-8a4c44266d58","timestamp":"2026-04-03T01:49:10.388Z","parentId":"863e308c-d1fc-45cc-9816-4c97f72ce0ce"}
